            <h2>Inflected Infinitive</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">T</span>o recap, the <strong>infinitive</strong> is the base
                form of the verb.
                In Old English, infinitives end in <strong>-an</strong>. When verbs are inflected, the
                <strong>-an</strong> ending is removed,
                and the inflection is added: for example, the infinitive of the Old English verb 'to flow' is
                '<em>flowan</em>'; the root
                is <em>flow-</em>; and the present singular inflection/ending <strong>-e</strong> is added to give us
                '<em>Ic flowe - I flow</em>'.</p>

            <p>In addition to being the 'dictionary form' of the verb, equivalent to modern English 'to hear', the
                infinitive can also be used
                following an auxiliary or inflected verb
                for example in the sentence
                '<em>He het streamas flowan - He ordered streams to flow</em>'. The <em>auxiliary verb + infinitive</em> is a very
                common construction,
                as it is in modern English,
                and here the infinitive <em>flowan</em> can be translated directly by the modern English infinitive 'to
                flow'.</p>
            <div class="text-center">
                <div class="grammar-box darkgrey-bg">
                    <div class="inline-block">
                        <span class="red-text big-text border-bottom">He</span><br>
                        <span class="red-text">Subject</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="inline-block">
                        <span class="green-text big-text"><span class="border-bottom">het</span> </span><br>
                        <span class="green-text">Inflected verb</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="inline-block">
                        <span class="yellow-text big-text border-bottom">streamas</span><br>
