                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>However, in Old English we also come across what is known as an <strong>inflected infinitive</strong>.
                This inflection follows the preposition 'to', and rather than the infinitive form, the ending
                <strong>-enne</strong> is added. So the inflected infinitive of 'to flow'
                is '<em>to flowenne</em>'. Because this inflection can be used for emphasis, it is often best translated
                as '<em>in order to</em>', in this case '<em>in order to flow</em>''. The inflected
                infinitive also sometimes follows the verb '<em>beon - to be</em>', and here it usually expresses some
                kind of obligation, and can be translated
                using 'must', 'should' or 'ought'. See the examples below, both using the inflected infinitive of the
                verb '<em>healdan - to keep or hold</em>:
                '<em>Hie timbrodon byrig, þæt land to healdenne - They built forts in order to hold the land</em>' and
                <em>'Eow mæst þearf is daglic fasten to healdenne -
                    - 'It is very needful for you to hold daily fasts</em>'.
            </p>
